{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The outbound classification request includes the full taxonomy label list every time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure mode is at the module boundary between prompt/request builder and API client wiring. A pure unit test of a helper can miss dropped labels during request assembly/serialization across modules; real network is not required.","test_description":"Wire the classifier with a fake in-process API client that records the actual outbound payload. Invoke classification with a sample document and assert the sent request contains all configured labels (no omissions, no truncation, no reordering assumptions unless required).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"If API returns a label outside taxonomy, module returns \"unknown\".","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is local validation/mapping logic on returned label. No real I/O or multi-module interaction is strictly required to catch forwarding of invalid labels.","test_description":"Call the response-normalization/classification-result handling function with an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\") and assert output is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Same document yields same classification across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model output stability; mocks are deterministic and can hide real nondeterminism/drift. This is not just pipeline wiring, it is model-behavior dependent.","test_description":"Run N repeated real API classifications for the identical document under fixed model/settings and assert all returned labels match; record flake rate over repeated test runs to detect nondeterministic variance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Token consumption for a typical document stays within configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure often appears at provider token accounting boundary (actual request framing/tokenization vs local estimate). Mocked token counts can systematically miss over-budget calls.","test_description":"Execute a real classification call for a representative document and assert provider-reported usage (or authoritative metering source) is <= configured token budget for that call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On rate-limit signal, module waits and retries instead of returning immediate error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is retry policy wiring across client/error handling/timer logic. This can be caught with controlled in-process doubles; real external API is not strictly necessary for this behavior.","test_description":"Use a fake API client that returns rate-limit error on first call and success on second. Verify classifier delays according to retry policy and ultimately returns successful label rather than propagating the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
